\f1\b0\fs22 \cf0 The setting and timeline may seem at first to be {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/TheMiddleAges"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 The Middle Ages}}, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/UsefulNotes/TheThirteenAmericanColonies"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 The Colonial Period}}, or some {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/FantasyCounterpartCulture"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 Fantasy Counterpart Culture}} thereof, but when you look closer, you find polyester, robots, or other high-tech toys in between the horse-drawn wagons and wattle-and-daub buildings. There\'92s generally no rhyme or reason for 
\f2\i which
\f1\i0  technologies are anachronistically present besides the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/RuleOfCool"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 Rule of Cool}}. Sometimes these may be leftovers from a {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/LostTechnology"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 lost technological civilization}}, or perhaps it could be that science developed along a different path than ours, allowing for more advanced technology in one field, while stagnating in others, but most of the time there is no explanation whatsoever for the bizarre mix of medieval and futuristic.\
Schizo Tech is a key component of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/PunkPunk"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 Punk Punk}}. It\'92s also the foundation for {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/FantasyGunControl"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 Fantasy Gun Control}}. Compare {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/DecadeDissonance"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 Decade Dissonance}} for when one side has all the cool toys. When a story nominally set in a real-life historical period has this problem, you\'92ve got yourself some tasty {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/AnachronismStew"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 Anachronism Stew}}. It may be because an {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/HigherTechSpecies"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 isolated branch of mankind}} created an {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/AdvancedAncientAcropolis"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 Advanced Ancient Acropolis}}. {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/AfterTheEnd"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 After the End}} is normally a good justification of this; often resulting in {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/ScavengerWorld"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 Scavenger World}}, especially when you have a faction with {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/LowCultureHighTech"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 Low Culture, High Tech}}.\
When evaluating a candidate for this trope, try not to confuse anachronisms with non-western-isms. For example, a kimono can be just as modern as a three-piece suit, if not more so. Likewise, do not confuse anachronism for cosmetic purposes with anachronism of technological capability. For example, though you will see lots of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/ZeppelinsFromAnotherWorld"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 Zeppelins from Another World}} at work in Schizo Tech, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/UsefulNotes/Airships"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 Airships}} themselves are not more or less advanced than airplanes or helicopters, just suited to different situations\'97namely, ones that value endurance, payload and fuel efficiency over speed and maneuverability. Alternatively, a judge wearing an eighteenth century robe and wig while judging cybercrime cases is not schizo tech, but simply a remnant of the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/GoodOldWays"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 Good Old Ways}}. And again, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Administrivia/TropesAreTools"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 Tropes Are Still Not Bad}}. It\'92s also worth noting that in the alternate history of a candidate, the culture and style may simply be different, so while their older architecture may seem to jar with their higher levels of technology, it may be that that style of architecture is just \'93in\'94 at that time. In dealing with other cultures, also remember that the concept of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/TechnologyLevels"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 Technology Levels}} is flawed, and that {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/AliensNeverInventedTheWheel"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 real societies are not obliged to all invent the same things in the same order, and may miss some inventions entirely.}}\
Most comic book universes have this trope as a natural consequence: the wondrous science held by the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/ReedRIchardsIsUseless"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 heroes}} and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/CutLexLuthorACheck"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 villains}} would, if even partially distributed, violate the surprisingly mundane world that divides the superhero genre from outright {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/SpeculativeFiction"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 Speculative Fiction}}. Examples and subversions are noted below.\
This trope has frequently been {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/TruthInTelevision"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 Truth in Television}} depending on the circumstances, with historical works involving {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/UsefulNotes/WorldWarI"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 World War I}} and other major events that were technological \'91kitchen sink\'92 like affairs (with cavalry charges co-existing with airplane bombing runs) one hundred percent qualifying. Beware: Many sci-fi settings that aren\'92t {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/MohsScaleOfSciFiHardness"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 harder than diamond}} can become this 
